            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Is there a Condorcet candidate? If so, who? If not, why not?</p>
                </statement>
                
                <solution>
                    <p>A (80) v B (120): B wins</p>
                    <p>A (150) v C (50): A wins</p>
                    <p>B (70) v C (130): C wins</p>
                    <p> No one can beat all the other candidates, so there is no Condorcet 
                        candidate.</p>
                </solution>
                
                <answer>No. No one can beat all other candidates in a head-to-head comparison.
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Who wins using the Borda Count method?</p>
                </statement>
                
                <solution>
                    <me>A = 80 \cdot 3 + 70 \cdot 2 + 50 \cdot 1 = 430</me>
                    <me>B = 80 \cdot 1 + 70 \cdot 3 + 50 \cdot 2 = 390</me>
                    <me>C = 80 \cdot 2 + 70 \cdot 1 = 50 \cdot 3 = 380</me>
                    <p>A wins</p>
                </solution>
                
                <answer>A</answer>
            </exercise>
            
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>If C drops out of the race, who will using the Borda Count method?
                        Was one of the fairness criteria violated? If so, which one?</p>
                </statement>
                
                <solution>
                    <p>The preference schedule is now:
                        <table>
                            <tabular halign = "center">
                                <row header = "yes" bottom = "minor">
                                    <cell></cell>
                                    <cell>80</cell>
                                    <cell>70</cell>
